                </a></li></ul></div><p><strong>Figure 1.  <span>A male fiddler crab <em>Uca terpsichores</em> with a sand hood as a sexual signal.</span></strong></p><a id="article1.body1.sec1.fig1.caption1.p1" name="article1.body1.sec1.fig1.caption1.p1"></a><p>The male waves its enlarged claw to attract females to its burrow which has a sand hood at the entrance. Males are about 1 cm wide. Hoods project above the visual horizon of crabs. This makes them conspicuous landmarks that help crabs find burrows.</p>
